 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":5,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":50,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Combes was born in 1332, in Gittisham, Devon, England, his father, Sir William Combes, was 30 and his mother, Mrs. William de Combes, was 25. He married Mrs. Henry de Combs in 1357, in Gittisham, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1400, in his hometown, at the age of 68, and was buried in Gittisham, Devon, England."},"et":{"1332–1400":"1332–1400","1337–1403":"1337–1403","1376–1440":"1376–1440","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1307–Female":"1307–Surnud","1327":"1327","1403":"1403","1337":"1337","1357":"1357","1302":"1302","1400":